    <stitle>VT-365 Diesel Engine Diagnostics (2002) - PERFORMANCE DIAGNOSTICS - Test Procedures - Fuel</stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="3">
        <title>Fuel</title>
        <figure id="f2400611" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figD31/D3137.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
        </figure>
        <para>
            <emph type="bold">Purpose</emph>
        </para>
        <para>To check fuel level and quality for efficient engine operation</para>
        <para>
            <emph type="bold">Tools</emph>
        </para>
        <randlist type="bullet">
            <item>
                <para>Clear container (approximately 1 Quart or 1 Liter)</para>
            </item>
        </randlist>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>To avoid serious personal injury, possible death, or damage to the engine or vehicle, read all
                    safety instructions in the foreword of this manual. Follow all warnings, cautions, and notes.
                </para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <para>
            <emph type="bold">Procedure</emph>
        </para>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>To avoid serious personal injury, possible death, or damage to the engine or vehicle - comply with
                    the following when taking fuel sample:
                </para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>Do not smoke.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Keep away from open flames and sparks.</para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Take fuel sample from fuel tank. Fuel must be the correct grade, clean, and undiluted.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f2400612" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figD31/D31110.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Fuel drain</caption>
        </figure>
        <figure id="f2400613" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figD31/D31116.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Open fuel drain valve</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Run a hose from the fuel drain tube to a clear container and open the drain.</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Cold weather can cause fuel waxing in some grades of diesel fuel. Waxing will restrict or stop
                        fuel flow through the fuel filter.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check for gasoline or kerosene in the diesel fuel.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check for sediment or water in the fuel sample.</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Some sediment or water could be found in the fuel sample, if the fuel filter was not serviced
                        or drained for a long time. Take another sample to determine fuel quality.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If unit was run out of fuel, make sure the fuel system was primed. See Section 4 in this
                        manual for procedure.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If all three of the following conditions are noted, see Combustion Leaks to Fuel in Section
                        4.
                    </para>
                    <randlist type="bullet">
                        <item>
                            <para>Fuel system will not prime</para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>White to black exhaust smoke</para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>Pulsating fuel pressure</para>
                        </item>
                    </randlist>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <para>
            <emph type="bold">Possible Causes</emph>
        </para>
        <randlist type="bullet">
            <item>
                <para>No fuel in tank.</para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>The in-line fuel valve (if equipped) could be shut off.</para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>Fuel supply line could be broken or crimped.</para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>The tank pickup tube could be clogged or cracked.</para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>Supplemental filters or water separators may be plugged or leaking allowing air to enter the fuel
                    system.
                </para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>Water or contaminants in fuel tank.</para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>Ice in fuel lines.</para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>Debris in fuel tank.</para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>Cloudy fuel indicates that fuel grade is unsuitable for cold temperatures.</para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>Fuel could be waxed or jelled. (usually Grade 2-D).</para>
            </item>
        </randlist>
    </svcproc>
